Sure! Here's a simple implementation of the Bubble Sort algorithm in Java:

```java
public class BubbleSort {
    public static void bubbleSort(int[] arr) {
        int n = arr.length;
        boolean swapped;
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
            swapped = false;
            for (int j = 0; j < n - 1 - i; j++) {
                if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                    // Swap arr[j] and arr[j + 1]
                    int temp = arr[j];
                    arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                    arr[j + 1] = temp;
                    swapped = true;
                }
            }
            // If no two elements were swapped by inner loop, then break
            if (!swapped) break;
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};
        System.out.println("Unsorted array:");
        for (int num : arr) {
            System.out.print(num + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();

        bubbleSort(arr);

        System.out.println("Sorted array:");
        for (int num : arr) {
            System.out.print(num + " ");
        }
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
1. **Outer Loop**: Runs from the start of the array to the second last element.
2. **Inner Loop**: Runs from the start of the array to the last unsorted element.
3. **Swapping**: If the current element is greater than the next element, they are swapped.
4. **Optimization**: If no elements were swapped during a pass, the array is already sorted, and the loop can be terminated early.

You can run this code to see how the Bubble Sort algorithm sorts the array.

