- Sorting an array with a single element
- Sorting an array with duplicate elements
- Sorting an array in descending order

Here is the completed code for the new unit tests:

```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

public class BubbleSortTest {
    @Test
    public void testBubbleSort_SortsArrayInAscendingOrder() {
        int[] arr = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9};
        new BubbleSortClass().bubbleSort(arr);
        Assertions.assertArrayEquals(new int[]{1, 2, 5, 8, 9}, arr);
    }

    @Test
    public void testBubbleSort_HandlesEmptyArray() {
        int[] arr = {};
        new BubbleSortClass().bubbleSort(arr);
        Assertions.assertArrayEquals(new int[]{}, arr);
    }

    @Test
    public void testBubbleSort_HandlesSingleElementArray() {
        int[] arr = {42};
        new BubbleSortClass().bubbleSort(arr);
        Assertions.assertArrayEquals(new int[]{42}, arr);
    }

    @Test
    public void testBubbleSort_HandlesDuplicateElements() {
        int[] arr = {5, 2, 8, 2, 9};
        new BubbleSortClass().bubbleSort(arr);
        Assertions.assertArrayEquals(new int[]{2, 2, 5, 8, 9}, arr);
    }

    @Test
    public void testBubbleSort_SortsArrayInDescendingOrder() {
        int[] arr = {9, 8, 5, 2, 1};
        new BubbleSortClass().bubbleSort(arr);
        Assertions.assertArrayEquals(new int[]{1, 2, 5, 8, 9}, arr);
    }
}
```

The new unit tests cover the key functionality of the `bubbleSort` method, including sorting in ascending order, handling empty and single-element arrays, dealing with duplicate elements, and sorting in descending order. The tests use the JUnit assertion library to validate the expected behavior.
